    { question: "Is Cambodia safe for tourists?", answer: "Cambodia is generally safe for tourists. Bag-snatching by motorbike is the main risk in Phnom Penh — hold bags on the building side when walking. Avoid walking alone in dark areas at night. Stick to marked paths in rural areas due to landmine legacy. Tourist areas (Siem Reap, Phnom Penh, Kampot, beaches) are well-traveled and safe with normal precautions." },
    { question: "How much money should I bring to Cambodia?", answer: "Budget travelers: $20-35/day covers hostels, street food, and shared transport. Mid-range: $50-100/day for boutique hotels, restaurants, and private tours. Luxury: $150+/day for resorts and fine dining. US dollars are accepted everywhere — bring clean, undamaged bills. ATMs dispense USD in most cities. Cash is king outside major tourist areas." },
    { question: "What currency does Cambodia use?", answer: "Cambodia uses a dual-currency system: US dollars and Cambodian riel (KHR). Dollars are used for most transactions over $1. You'll receive riel as change for amounts under $1 (4,000 KHR = $1 USD). Bring clean, undamaged US bills — torn or marked notes are often rejected. ATMs dispense US dollars in most cities." },
    { question: "What is the best way to get around Cambodia?", answer: "Between cities: Giant Ibis or Mekong Express buses (comfortable, $10-18 per route). Within cities: tuk-tuks ($1-3 short rides), Grab/PassApp in Phnom Penh. Phnom Penh to Siem Reap: 6-hour bus ($15-18) or 45-minute flight ($60-120). To islands: speedboat from Sihanoukville to Koh Rong ($15-20). Scooter rental: $5-10/day for experienced riders." },
